<Base title="FAQ" description="Frequently asked questions about substrate.">
  <h1>FAQ</h1>

  <h2>Is substrate stable for production use?</h2>
  <p>
    Substrate is at v0.8. The CLI surface and config schema are stable for
    everyday use; v1.0 will lock semver on the schema. Production users
    should be comfortable with minor schema migrations between 0.x bumps.
  </p>

  <h2>How does substrate compare to shadcn?</h2>
  <p>
    Substrate and shadcn share a model: <em>framework + opinionated content,
    scaffolded into your repo, owned by you</em>. Substrate is for codebase
    automation (audits, standards, scaffolds, AI bridges); shadcn is for
    UI components. The upgrade story differs: substrate ships a real three-
    way merge in <code>substrate upgrade</code> so you can pull in framework
    improvements; shadcn punts on upgrades.
  </p>

  <h2>Why "substrate"?</h2>
  <p>
    "The rhythm of repeatable patterns; standards become the system's
    heartbeat." Names matching the editorial-portfolio convention
    (Blaze, Chorus, Substrate) ship best alongside their siblings.
  </p>

  <h2>Why is OP4Z mentioned in some docs but not in substrate's content?</h2>
  <p>
    OP4Z is the project where substrate's <code>./exc</code> automation system
    was originally built. Substrate is the public framework extraction. OP4Z
    keeps its specific RULES content, task helpers, and brand strings
    private; substrate ships the abstractions. Per the locked design, public
    substrate is ~60% reusable framework, ~40% scaffold templates.
  </p>

  <h2>Does substrate collect telemetry?</h2>
  <p>
    Substrate has <strong>opt-in</strong> telemetry. Off by default. On first
    run, you'll be prompted; if you opt in, anonymous usage events (command
    name, audit type, error type, substrate version, OS family) are recorded.
    No project paths, no user identifiers, no rule body content. v0.8 emits
    to <code>~/.config/substrate/telemetry.log</code> only — no real endpoint
    is wired yet. v1.0 will add the optional collector.
  </p>

  <h2>How do I license substrate?</h2>
  <p>
    Code is <a href="https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT">MIT</a>. Content
    (the standards docs, audit playbooks, this site) is
    <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">CC-BY 4.0</a>.
    You're free to fork, adapt, and ship in commercial software. Attribution
    is required for the content license; the code license has no
    attribution requirement.
  </p>
</Base>
